# Deploy Convention

When a deploy is needed, always use `op-firebase-deploy` (global script on PATH).

## Commands

```bash
npm run deploy                 # full deploy (hosting + functions + rules + storage)
npm run deploy:hosting         # hosting only
npm run deploy:functions       # functions only
op-firebase-deploy --only hosting,functions  # any Firebase target combo
```

## How it works

- `op-firebase-deploy` reads a service account key from 1Password (`Private/Firebase Deploy - {project}/credential`)
- Auto-detects the Firebase project from `.firebaserc`, then looks up the matching 1Password item
- Writes the key to a temp file (`umask 077`), sets `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS`, runs `firebase deploy --non-interactive`, cleans up on exit
- The only interactive step is the 1Password biometric prompt (Touch ID). No `firebase login`, `gcloud auth login`, or browser prompts needed
- The service account key never expires unless explicitly deleted
- Also supports `authorized_user` ADC tokens (auto-validates and self-heals if stale)

## First-time setup for a new project

```bash
op-firebase-setup                    # auto-detect from .firebaserc
op-firebase-setup my-project-id      # explicit project ID
```

This creates a `firebase-deployer` service account, grants deploy roles, generates a key, and stores it in 1Password as `Firebase Deploy - {project}`. Run once per project.

## Key rotation

The service account key does not expire. To rotate it if compromised:

```bash
op-firebase-setup                    # generates a new key and updates 1Password
```

To manually rotate or delete old keys:

```bash
gcloud iam service-accounts keys list \
  --iam-account=firebase-deployer@PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com
gcloud iam service-accounts keys delete KEY_ID \
  --iam-account=firebase-deployer@PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com
```

## Rules

- Never run `firebase deploy` or `npx firebase deploy` directly — always use `op-firebase-deploy` or `npm run deploy`
- Never run `firebase login` or `gcloud auth login` as part of a deploy flow
- Never store or print credentials; only use `op://` references in committed files
